    "name": "COU2: Ventricular assist device use (Class III)",
    "type": "ContextOfUse"
  },
  "claim": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/claim/vad-hemolysis-cfd-credibility",
    "type": "Claim",
    "name": "CFD model credibly predicts absolute hemolysis index below clinical threshold for Class III VAD across all five operating points",
    "description": "The CFD hemolysis model, employing a power-law damage accumulation formulation with Lagrangian particle tracking, is assessed as credible for predicting the normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) in absolute terms for the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump operated under VAD conditions. Across the five flow-speed combinations specified in the COU, Monte Carlo uncertainty quantification (n=500 Latin hypercube samples) demonstrates that the 95th-percentile NIH prediction remains below the accepted clinical threshold of 0.01 g/100 L. The claim scope is restricted to the geometric envelope of the FDA generic pump and the operating envelope defined in the COU; extrapolation to patient-specific geometries is explicitly excluded. Credibility is asserted at MRL 5 with all assessed factors meeting or exceeding required gradation levels after corrective actions documented in validation reports VR-2024-001 through VR-2024-007.",
    "purpose": "Support regulatory submission to FDA demonstrating computational evidence of hemolysis safety for a Class III VAD device in lieu of additional in-vitro hemolysis testing beyond the predicate comparison.",
    "scope": "FDA generic centrifugal blood pump geometry; VAD operating envelope (3000–5000 RPM, 3–7 L/min); NIH as primary QoI; MRL 5 credibility requirements per ASME V&V 40-2018."
  },
